    "locales": {
      "en": {
        "name": "Kalashnikov AS-2 7.62x39 assault rifle",
        "shortName": "AS-2",
        "description": "The AS-2 (Avtomat Specialnyj; Russian: Автомат Специальный) and AS-1 are 5.45x39mm and 7.62x39mm Russian prototype bullpup assault rifles developed and revealed in 2013 by, the formerly Izhmash, Kalashnikov Concern. Its designer was Vladimir Zlobin, who formerly worked in Tula, and became the chief designer of the factory in Ivhevsk in 2012. The gun's development was originally ordered by the FSB and saw some interest by the Russian Army. Minister of Defense Sergei Shoigu announced that it would enter the 'Ratnik' trials that saw the eventual adoption of the AK-12. However, these rifles never ended up in the 2014 round of testing, with Zlobin's AK-12 prototype and the 7.62x39mm AK-103-3 (proto-AK-400) being submitted as the Concern's bids instead. This occurred after irredeemable problems with the rifles were revealed in factory and FSB testing beforehand, such as in the hands of a former FSB agent and gun designer, 'Kochevnik'."
      }
    },
